@Node 11 " History "

For brevity, I've deleted up to the version 4.0 stuff from this file.

Press @{"This button" link 19} to see the updates for THIS version.

Version 5.0 - Added new file (program-generated) called "ODDS.DAT".  This
file is updated with each use of the lottery.  It keeps track of what numbers
get picked by the computer-generated lottery, so you can see what numbers are
"hot".  It costs the user $10000 to "buy" an Odds Sheet, and they don't get
to use it until their NEXT turn.  This will be more accurate the more the
lotto is played, so encourage your users to play it a lot!

Version 4.9 - Fixed reported bug in attack phase.  Simple mistake on my part.

Version 4.8 - Dropped another 2K by FINISHING what I started in 4.7.
Also found out that the library call returns a number between 0 and what you
pass, NOT 1 and what you pass, as I assumed.  Helps to read the docs ;)
This is the first version with AmigaGuide documentation included in the archive.

Version 4.7 - Standardized the RANDOM calls, using the call in the
MEBBSAREXX.LIBRARY library instead of the one built in to Arexx.  The one in
Arexx is HARDLY random.

Version 4.6 - Another minor stupidity fix.  I was shortening the code and my
global replace for a routine name didn't get renamed everywhere for some
reason.

Versions 4.4 - 4.5 - Minor stupidity fixes

Version 4.3 - Found some more things, checked stuff that I wasn't before.

Version 4.2 - First public release of new code.  Lots of things cleaned up.
Changed my Dev # back since I'm a CSR again ;)

Version 4.1 - Limited beta release, first conversion to MEBBSNET's new AREXX.

Version 4.0 - Had to change my developer's number since I'm not a CSR anymore.
Also added the ability to buy ONE turn's worth of protection.  Be sure to copy
the new INSTRUCTIONS.TXT file OVER your existing one, since it documents the
changes for your users.  Also, fixed the INUSE thing so that, if it finds an
INUSE from the same LINE as the current user, it means its bogus.  If its a
different line, it exits cleanly like it used to.  Thanks to Jason Gouger for
suggesting it.


@EndNode

